by having the combination of a relatively large (SVL = 
<quantity box="[434,533,1393,1417]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.29" pageId="9" pageNumber="537" unit="mm" value="129.0">129 mm</quantity>
) robust body (PEC/SVL = 0.15); seven supralabials and infralabials; midline contact of the supranasals; prefrontals not in contact; frontoparietal contacting three supraoculars; large postinterparietal present; eight superciliaries; two postsuboculars, the first being small; one or two primary and three secondary and tertiary temporals; eight nuchal scales; a deep postnasal groove extending from the nasal scale to below the anterior portion of the eye and lying below the anterior loreals and lower preocular and above the second and third supralabials; scaly lower eyelid, no window; 45 midbody scale rows; 95 paravertebral scale rows; 98 ventral scale rows; 34 caudal scale rows at the tenth subcaudal; eight large precloacal scales; smooth to weakly keeled subdigital finger lamellae, 10 lamellae on third finger; keeled subdigital toe lamellae, 16 lamellae on fourth toe; low, round, small, palmar scales numbering seven across the base of the palm; head pattern consisting of a dark, continuous frontal and occipital band separated by a yellowish band; dark occipital band not confluent with lighter color of dorsum and tail. These characters are scored across all species in the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Rooji" authorityYear="1915" box="[1109,1265,1752,1777]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Lygosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="537" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bampfyldei">
<emphasis box="[1109,1265,1752,1777]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">L. bampfyldei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group in 
<tableCitation captionStart="TABLE 2" captionStartId="16.[147,226,490,511]" captionText="TABLE 2. Stanđarđ đescriptive anđ điagnostic (shađeđ) characters among đifferent combinations of species of the Lygosoma bampfyldei group. All measurements are in millimeters. / = đata unobtainable. Abbreviations are listeđ in the Materials anđ methođs." pageId="9" pageNumber="537">Table 2</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="537" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1284,2029]" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1824,1849]" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">Distribution.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Werner" authorityYear="1900" box="[359,598,1824,1849]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Lygosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="537" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="schneideri">
<emphasis box="[359,598,1824,1849]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">Lygosoma schneideri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[875,923,1825,1849]" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">type</typeStatus>
locality. 
<bibRefCitation box="[1027,1153,1825,1849]" pageId="9" pageNumber="537" refId="ref7752" refString="Das, I. (2010) A Field Guide to the Reptiles of South-east Asia. Bloomsbury, London, 325 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.1108 / RR- 08 - 2016 - 0210" type="book">Das (2010)</bibRefCitation>
reports this species from “north-western 
<collectingRegion box="[328,421,1861,1885]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
(Indrajiri, 
<collectingRegion box="[547,713,1860,1885]" country="Indonesia" name="Riau" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">Riau Province</collectingRegion>
)” however the 
<typeStatus box="[888,936,1861,1885]" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">type</typeStatus>
locality listed by 
<bibRefCitation box="[1144,1310,1861,1885]" pageId="9" pageNumber="537" refId="ref9568" refString="Werner, F. (1910) Uber neue oder seltene Reptilien des Naturhistorischen Museums in Hamburg. ii. Eidechsen des Jahrbuch der Hamburgischen Wissenschaftlichen Anstalten, 27 (1909), 1 (Supplement), 1910, 1 - 46." type="journal article">Werner (1910)</bibRefCitation>
“Indragiri, Djapura” is in southeastern 
<collectingRegion box="[462,555,1897,1921]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[571,636,1896,1921]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="1.[151,250,1219,1241]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,483,1197]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1436,483,1197]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURE 1. Distribution of the species of the Lygosoma bampfyldei group in Sundaland. Stars designate the location of the type localities for L. bampfyldei along the Rajang River, Sarawak, East Malaysia; L. peninsulare sp. nov. from 13.5 km east of Jeli, Kelantan, Peninsular Malaysia; L. kinabatanganensis sp. nov. from the Kinabatangan District, Deramakot camp (Deramakot Sabah Forestry Department), Sabah, East Malaysia; and L. schneideri from Indragiri, Djapura, Sumatra, Indonesia. Colors are coded to match those of the Figure 3." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1298206/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="538" pageId="9" pageNumber="537" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1284,2029]" lastBlockId="10.[151,1436,151,215]" lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="538" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1933,1957]" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">Remarks.</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation box="[332,541,1932,1957]" pageId="9" pageNumber="537" refId="ref7660" refString="Boulenger, G. A. (1912) A Fertebrate Fauna of the Malay Peninsula from the Isthmus of Kra to Singapore Including Adjacent Islands. Taylor and Francis, London, 314 pp. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 10813" type="book">Boulenger (1912)</bibRefCitation>
placed 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Werner" authorityYear="1900" box="[649,898,1932,1957]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Lygosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="537" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="schneideri">
<emphasis box="[649,898,1932,1957]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">Lygosoma schneideri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the synonymy of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Rooji" authorityYear="1915" box="[1182,1347,1932,1957]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Lygosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="537" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bampfyldei">
<emphasis box="[1182,1347,1932,1957]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">L. bampfyldei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in his redescription of the latter. Our analyses indicate that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Werner" authorityYear="1900" box="[751,899,1968,1993]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Lygosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="537" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="schneideri">
<emphasis box="[751,899,1968,1993]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">L. schneideri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is considerably different from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="de Rooji" authorityYear="1915" box="[1251,1407,1968,1993]" class="Reptilia" family="Scincidae" genus="Lygosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Squamata" pageId="9" pageNumber="537" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="bampfyldei">
<emphasis box="[1251,1407,1968,1993]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">L. bampfyldei</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having two vs. three suboculars, a postparietal scale (
<figureCitation box="[777,849,2004,2029]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="2.[151,250,886,908]" captionTargetBox="[200,1376,213,823]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,865]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 2. A) Right lateral view of the head of the holotype of Lygosoma kinabatanganensis sp. nov. (FMNH 76226) from the Kinabatangan District, Deramakot camp (Deramakot Sabah Forestry Department), Sabah, East Malaysia and B) dorsal view of head of the holotype of L. schneideri from Djpura, Indragiri, Sumatra, Indonesia illustrating the positional relationship and size of some of the head scales. Terminology is adapted from Taylor (1935). AL = anterior loreal, Cs = chinshield; F = frontal, Fn = frontonasal, Fp = frontoparietal, IL = infralabial, Ip = interparietal, M = mental, N = nasal, Nu = nuchal, P = parietal, Pf = prefrontal, PI = postinterparietal, PL = posterior loreal, Pm = postmental, Pos = postsubocular, Pro = preocular, Prs = presubocular, PT = primary temporal, Psl = postsupralabial, Pto = postocular, R = rostral, Sl = supralabial, Sn = supranasal, So = supraocular, ST = secondary temporal, and TT = tertiary temporal. * = superciliary. Illustration by LLG." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1298208/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="537">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
), 45 vs. 36–40 midbody scale rows, 95 vs. 82–85 paravertebral scale rows, 34 vs. 28–30 scale rows around the tail at the 10th subcaudal, and a significantly (
<emphasis box="[1347,1355,156,179]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="538">t</emphasis>
= -6, 
<emphasis box="[1422,1436,156,179]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="538">p</emphasis>
= 0.004) more robust (PEC/SVL = 0.15) vs. a slender (PEC/SVL = 0.12–0.13) body (
<figureCitation box="[1108,1177,190,215]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1451,1473]" captionTargetBox="[176,1396,723,1417]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,700,1430]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Comparisons of body stature of the types of A, Lygosoma scheideri (BM 4743) from Djpura, Indragiri, Sumatra, Indonesia; B, syntype of Lygosoma bampfyldei (BMNH 1946.8.10.84) from the Rejan River, Sarawak, East Malaysia; C, L. kinabatanganensis sp. nov. (FMNH 76226) from the Kinabatangan District, Deramakot camp (Deramakot Sabah Forestry Department), Sabah, East Malaysia; and D, L. peninsulare sp. nov. (LSUHC 13857) from 13.5 km east of Jeli, Kelantan, Peninsular Malaysia." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1298212/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="538">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
